Allie Phillips, a young Tennessee woman who runs a daycare from home and has a young daughter, Adalie, was delighted to learn she was pregnant with a second daughter, Miley, in 2022. Miley was deemed ‚Äúincompatible with life‚Äù at around 19 weeks, and Allie was faced with the decision many women must grapple with now that Roe has fallen: to leave the state to receive abortion care, or to continue her pregnancy as her daughter deteriorated, threatening Allie‚Äôs life and fertility. She chose the former, and documented the difficult, time-sensitive process to her nearly 300,000 TikTok followers.

Her state representative was no help‚Äì Allie learned he hadn‚Äôt considered cases like hers in banning abortion because he thought, shockingly, that only first pregnancies could have complications. She‚Äôs now running for that very seat in the statehouse, and joins Next Question today to make her inspiring case for change.
